item.content:encoded:
We use the QuickLaTeX plugin and rendering engine to display TeX on the wiki. This page has instructions on how to use it. For the most part, things work as they do with other engines.
<h1>Guide</h1>
<h2>Writing</h2>
LaTeX is by default enabled sitewide. Write it like you would in a TeX editor. Math mode can be entered using the familiar <code>!$ ... $, !\[ ... \]</code> or <code>!\begin{equation} ... \end{equation}</code> commands. Others can be entered using the <code>\begin</code> command.

Available environments are: <code>equation</code>, <code>align</code>, <code>displaymath</code>, <code>eqnarray</code>, <code>multline</code>, <code>flalign</code>, <code>gather</code>, and <code>alignat</code>. Others may be usable, but there may be nuances to using them (see below for an "as we find it" list of these).
<h3>Example</h3>
<strong>Source:</strong>
<pre>At first, we sample !$f(x)$ in the !$N$ (!$N$ is odd) equidistant points around !$x^*$:
!\[
f_k = f(x_k),\: x_k = x^*+kh,\: k=-\frac{N-1}{2},\dots,\frac{N-1}{2}
\]
where !$h$ is some step.
Then we interpolate points !$\{(x_k,f_k)\}$ by polynomial
!\begin{equation} \label{eq:poly}
P_{N-1}(x)=\sum_{j=0}^{N-1}{a_jx^j}
\end{equation}
Its coefficients !$\{a_j\}$ are found as a solution of system of linear equations:
!\begin{equation} \label{eq:sys}
\left\{ P_{N-1}(x_k) = f_k\right\},\quad k=-\frac{N-1}{2},\dots,\frac{N-1}{2}
\end{equation}
Here are references to existing equations: (!\ref{eq:poly}), (!\ref{eq:sys}).
Here is reference to non-existing equation (!\ref{eq:unknown}).</pre>
<strong>Output:</strong>

At first, we sample $f(x)$ in the $N$ ($N$ is odd) equidistant points around $x^*$:
\[
f_k = f(x_k),\: x_k = x^*+kh,\: k=-\frac{N-1}{2},\dots,\frac{N-1}{2}
\]
where $h$ is some step.
Then we interpolate points $\{(x_k,f_k)\}$ by polynomial
\begin{equation} \label{eq:poly}
P_{N-1}(x)=\sum_{j=0}^{N-1}{a_jx^j}
\end{equation}
Its coefficients $\{a_j\}$ are found as a solution of system of linear equations:
\begin{equation} \label{eq:sys}
\left\{ P_{N-1}(x_k) = f_k\right\},\quad k=-\frac{N-1}{2},\dots,\frac{N-1}{2}
\end{equation}
Here are references to existing equations: (\ref{eq:poly}), (\ref{eq:sys}).
Here is reference to non-existing equation (\ref{eq:unknown}).
<h1>Nuances</h1>
Some things don't work exactly as they do in other engines (or as might be expected). As we find them, we'll list them below.
<h2>Errors due to Rendering Time</h2>
QuickLaTeX takes the TeX you write, renders an image, then saves a local copy. The first time you load a post will take longer due to this rendering. If there are many equations to render, then the page might take longer than the maximum execution time for PHP (~30s by default). You might see a message like:
<pre><b>Fatal error</b>: Maximum execution time of 30 seconds exceeded...</pre>
(Note, if PHP errors are off on the server, you'll just see a blank screen). Just refresh until it goes away (i.e. until all the images have been rendered). To avoid this, use the 'Preview Changes' button periodically while writing an article.
<h2>Alignment</h2>
TeX can be aligned by aligning the actual source code. This can result in some odd looking source, but some nice display.
<h2>Other Environments</h2>
Environments other than those listed above must must be wrapped in <code>![latex]...[/latex]</code>. This is a limitation of the QuickLaTeX plugin.
<h3>Example (Table)</h3>
<strong>Source:</strong>
<pre>![latex]
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|} \hline
$a$ &amp; $b$ \\ \hline
$c$ &amp; $d$ \\ \hline
\end{tabular}
[/latex]</pre>
<strong>Output:</strong>

[latex]
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|} \hline
$a$ &amp; $b$ \\ \hline
$c$ &amp; $d$ \\ \hline
\end{tabular}
[/latex]
<h3>Example (Algorithm)</h3>
<strong>Source</strong><strong>:</strong>
<pre>![latex]

\begin{algorithm}[H]
\KwData{this text}
\KwResult{how to write algorithm with \LaTeX2e }
initialization\;
\While{not at end of this document}{
read current\;
\eIf{understand}{
go to next section\;
current section becomes this one\;
}{
go back to the beginning of current section\;
}
}
\caption{How to write algorithms}
\end{algorithm}

[/latex]</pre>
<strong>Output (you'll need the <code>algorithm2e</code> plugin to see this):</strong>

[latex]

\begin{algorithm}[H]
\KwData{this text}
\KwResult{how to write algorithm with \LaTeX2e }
initialization\;
\While{not at end of this document}{
read current\;
\eIf{understand}{
go to next section\;
current section becomes this one\;
}{
go back to the beginning of current section\;
}
}
\caption{How to write algorithms}
\end{algorithm}

[/latex]
